5 748 M
(                                        Project: WG21/X3J16) s
5 737 M
(                                        Document Number: N1166/98-0023) s
5 726 M
(                                        Written by: Nathan Myers) s
5 715 M
(                                                    ncm@cantrip.org) s
5 704 M
(                                        Date: 1998 October 6) s
5 671 M
(Extension Namespace Recommendations) s
5 660 M
(-----------------------------------) s
5 638 M
(It is routine for other standards bodies to define extensions declared) s
5 627 M
(in standard headers.  Vendors are obliged to implement these extensions) s
5 616 M
(regardless of their effect on C++ Standard conformance.  Typically the) s
5 605 M
(extensions are defined for C only, and implementors must extrapolate) s
5 594 M
(those definitions to their C++ products.  In any case, these extensions) s
5 583 M
(create difficulties for standards \(plural\) conformance, particularly) s
5 572 M
(when different standards bodies \(or the same bodies at different times\)) s
5 561 M
(define different semantics for the same names in the same header.) s
5 539 M
(For example, the C9x group is considering a global name "clog" even) s
5 528 M
(though C++ already uses that name scoped as "std::clog".  Since the) s
5 517 M
(namespace directives can easily throw these names into conflict,) s
5 506 M
(implementors will be confronted with difficult choices.  The POSIX and) s
5 495 M
(X/Open groups define a variety of names specified to appear in standard) s
5 484 M
(headers, which for conformance must currently be guarded by #if blocks) s
5 473 M
(which rarely provide much actual help to users.  In <time.h>, the) s
5 462 M
(semantics different groups specify for the same names are incompatible.) s
5 451 M
(Standards bodies sometimes change the interfaces or semantics of their) s
5 440 M
(own previous extensions.) s
5 418 M
(While WG21 \(obviously?\) cannot specify non-standard interfaces, we can) s
5 407 M
(offer guidance to other standards bodies and \(perhaps more importantly\)) s
5 396 M
(to implementors translating standards to the C++ environment, to help) s
5 385 M
(avoid conflicts now and in the future.  The immediate moment offers a) s
5 374 M
(unique opportunity to prevent conflict, rather than try to ameliorate) s
5 363 M
(it later, by recommending a pattern for namespaces to encapsulate) s
5 352 M
(extensions.  This would be especially helpful for vendors adopting C) s
5 341 M
(extensions, because otherwise they must choose whether to make the names) s
5 330 M
(global, as in C, or put them in namespace std like the other names,) s
5 319 M
(or choose another namespace unlikely to match other vendors' choices.) s
5 297 M
(The essence of this proposal is to resolve to issue a short technical) s
5 286 M
(report, as soon as possible, recommending a pattern for namespace) s
5 275 M
(encapsulation of library extensions, and to outline what the report) s
5 264 M
(might include.) s
5 242 M
(For established standards we can recommend specific names; for others we) s
5 231 M
(can recommend a pattern that vendors can use when adopting \(or defining) s
5 220 M
(their own\) extensions.  Given adherence to a well-chosen pattern, the) s
5 209 M
(actual name a vendor or committee chooses for names we do not specify) s
5 198 M
(is less important than might be assumed, because namespace aliasing) s
5 187 M
(allows many conflicts to be resolved.) s
5 165 M
(For a hypothetical example, consider the C89 standard.  The C++ standard) s
5 154 M
(adopts most of its names into the std namespace, but there are some) s
5 143 M
(differences.  The C++ standard does not specify whether they are extern) s
5 132 M
("C" or "C++", and it defines replacements for some, such as strchr.) s
5 121 M
(Suppose a vendor had a need to provide, in addition to the C++ definitions,) s
5 110 M
(access to the actual C declarations -- declared extern "C" with C calling) s
5 99 M
(conventions.  These could certainly be wrapped in a namespace, but what) s
5 88 M
(would it be called?) s
5 66 M
(The pattern we suggest for the namespace name could be simple: the) s
5 55 M
(standards body name with a date stamp, followed by an alias lacking) s
5 44 M
(the date stamp, such as:) s
5 22 M
(  namespace _Iso_c_1989 {) s
5 11 M
(    extern "C" char* strchr\(char const* s, char const* p\);) s
_R
S
